As in the following?
try {
    // Do whatever
} catch (Exception ignored) {}

if (url == null) {
    try {
        // Do whatever
    } catch (Exception ignored) {}

    if (url == null) {
        try {
            // Do whatever
        } catch (Exception ignored) {}

        if (url == null || url.isEmpty()) {
           throw new ParsingException("whatever");
        }
    }
}
Or what do you mean? I'm not sure if I think that's cleaner. @TobiGr: What do you think?

Well, the code above has less url == null checks when the first extraction method returns a valid result and is therefore "faster". On the other hand when the url is empty, we might not throw an Exception, but return an empty string. So we'd need something like this.
try {
    // Do whatever
} catch (Exception ignored) {}

if (url == null) {
    try {
        // Do whatever
    } catch (Exception ignored) {}

    if (url == null) {
        try {
            // Do whatever
        } catch (Exception ignored) {}
    }
}
if (url == null || url.isEmpty()) {
    throw new ParsingException("whatever");
}
return url;
However, I do not understand, why we only check once whether the url is empty. We should do this either every time or not at all. I suggest to remove this isEmpty check, because the JSON fields won't be empty. They either exist and contain a valid value or do not exist. That's why I'd use the following, which might be more efficient when having a valid result at the beginning.
try {
    // Do whatever
} catch (Exception ignored) {}

if (url == null) {
    try {
        // Do whatever
    } catch (Exception ignored) {}

    if (url == null) {
        try {
            // Do whatever
        } catch (Exception ignored) {}

        if (url == null) {
            throw new ParsingException("whatever");
        }
    }
}

return url;
However, these kind of changes won't speed up anything in a way a user can recognize that. If you want, you can change it, but maybe we should ask @Stypox first, if we understood correctly what he meant.

